Voters in Guiana, Guadeloupe, Martinique and other overseas French territories headed to the polls on Saturday to cast their ballots in the first of two rounds of a parliamentary election. Voters in mainland France go the polls on Sunday.President Emmanuel Macron needs a clear majority in parliament to be able to pass laws and endorse his prime minister, Edouard Philippe.Read: Exploring Emmanuel Macron's 'revolution'Opinion polls have predicted that Macron's centrist La Republique en Marche (The Republic on the Move, LREM) party could win between 360 and 427 seats in the 577-strong parliament. There are a total of 7,882 candidates competing for the seats. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2eRsCFormer President Francois Hollande's Socialist Party could lose most of the 280 seats it held in the previous assembly.Far-right politician Marine Le Pen, the runner-up in the last month's presidential election with 34 percent of votes, is hoping for a parliamentary breakthrough for her National Front party. The final opinion polls gave her party a 17 percent share of the vote. The Republicans and its allies stood at around 20 percent, ten percent behind Macron's LREM with 30 percent.Poll stations open at 0800 (0600 UTC) and close at 1800 (1600 UTC) in most cities and two hours later in Paris and other big cities. Results will then be reported together with opinion poll estimates.Very few lawmakers are expected to be elected directly in the first round as they would need more than half of the votes.Read: Time for Macron to get to workOverseas French territories located outside of the European continent are administered by France and have representation in both houses of the French parliament - the National Assembly and the Senate. Overseas France includes island territories in the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian oceans, French Guiana on the South American continent, and several Peri-Antarctic islands. S